sers and `gff_admin`. Specifically, I am ensuring client users, not flagged as `gff_admin`, are filtered by `client_id` and that restricted visibility is properly enforced based on client association. It is necessary to clarify the correct visibility levels for each client.\n\n\n**Defining Visibility Checks**\n\nI'm now refining the visibility checks within the document route. I'm focusing on ensuring the correct filtering based on various visibility levels like `LEVEL_I (Client View)`, `LEVEL_IV (Restricted)`, `LEVEL_II (Sovereign Only)`, `LEVEL_III (Internal Use)`, and `LEVEL_V (Strictly Confidential)`. Specifically, I'm implementing RBAC policy logic to enforce visibility restrictions for client users and ensuring GFF admins have unrestricted access. I'm planning a clean check that filters documents based on `caller.role` and `caller.clientAssociation`.\n\n\n**Implementing POST Logic**\n\nI'm now implementing the POST endpoint logic. I'm ensuring only administrators can create documents, enforcing this in the `/app/api/v1/documents/route.ts` file, utilizing the `getAuthCaller` function. I will add an `if` statement to restrict document creation by non-administrators. This will block unauthorized requests from client users and handle the error gracefully. This will also ensure that any user who posts a document is authenticated.\n\n\n**Validating New Document Creation**\n\nI'm now zeroing in on the document creation POST logic, handling input validation within `/app/api/v1/documents/route.ts`. I am refining the error responses for invalid inputs to provide clearer feedback. This includes checking for required fields like title, client_id, and others, ensuring their data types and content are valid. I'm focusing on providing specific error messages.\n\n\n**Refining Client ID Validation**\n\nI'm now focusing on validating the `client_id` field in the POST request. I've added checks to ensure the `client_id` is present and valid, providing specific error messages for